<main class="stx">
  <div class="wrap">
    <a class="back" href="/aquintutor/labs">&#8592; All virtual labs</a>
    <div class="eyebrow">Structural Analysis &middot; Virtual lab</div>
    <h1>Trusses, beams, deflection &amp; <em>buckling</em></h1>
    <p class="lede">Six self-contained experiments, each a genuinely working structural solver written in plain JavaScript &mdash; no libraries. Plane trusses are solved member-by-member by the method of joints and cut directly by the method of sections; beams give live shear-force and bending-moment diagrams for point loads, distributed loads and applied moments; deflection is integrated by the Macaulay bracket method; influence lines are swept by a moving unit load; and Euler buckling plots the critical load against slenderness for four end conditions. Pick an experiment on the left, then move through Aim, Theory, Procedure, the live Simulation, a graded Self-assessment, and References.</p>

    <div class="shell">
      <!-- ===================== SIDEBAR ===================== -->
      <aside class="sidebar">
        <div class="stitle">Experiments</div>
        <div class="exp-item on" data-exp="1"><span class="num">1</span><span class="nm">Plane truss &mdash; method of joints (every member, T/C, reactions)</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="2"><span class="num">2</span><span class="nm">Method of sections &mdash; cut and solve one member directly</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="3"><span class="num">3</span><span class="nm">Shear-force &amp; bending-moment diagrams (point / UDL / moment)</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="4"><span class="num">4</span><span class="nm">Beam deflection &mdash; double integration / Macaulay</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="5"><span class="num">5</span><span class="nm">Influence lines for reaction, shear &amp; moment</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="6"><span class="num">6</span><span class="nm">Euler column buckling &mdash; critical load vs slenderness</span></div>
      </aside>

      <!-- ===================== MAIN PANEL ===================== -->
      <div class="main">

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 1 — METHOD OF JOINTS ============ -->
        <section class="exp on" id="exp-1">
          <h2 class="exp-head">1 &middot; Plane truss by the method of joints</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Select a determinate truss, apply a joint load, and solve every member force with tension/compression colouring and support reactions</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To determine the axial force in every member of a statically determinate plane truss using the method of joints, to identify each member as in tension or compression, and to verify the computed support reactions against global equilibrium.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>A <b>plane truss</b> is an assembly of straight two-force members pin-connected at joints and loaded only at the joints. Each member carries pure axial force &mdash; tension (pulling on its joints) or compression (pushing). A truss is <b>statically determinate and stable</b> when m + r = 2j, where m is the number of members, r the number of reaction components and j the number of joints; if m + r exceeds 2j it is redundant, if it is less the assembly is a mechanism.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Determinacy: m + r = 2 j &nbsp;&nbsp;(2j independent equilibrium equations)</div>
            <p>In the <b>method of joints</b> we isolate each pin and write the two scalar equilibrium equations of a concurrent force system. With member i making angle theta(i) with the horizontal at the joint, summing forces along x and y gives:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Sum Fx = 0:&nbsp; sum of N(i) cos theta(i) + Px = 0<br>Sum Fy = 0:&nbsp; sum of N(i) sin theta(i) + Py = 0</div>
            <p>Solving joints in an order where no joint has more than two unknown members yields every member force. Equivalently the whole truss is one linear system A&middot;N = L, where A is the 2j by (m + r) matrix of unit member direction cosines plus reaction columns, N the unknown member and reaction forces and L the applied joint loads. We assemble and solve that system by Gaussian elimination with partial pivoting, so a positive N means tension and a negative N means compression. Global checks &mdash; vertical reactions sum to the total downward load, and the moment about a support is zero &mdash; confirm the reactions.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b> and choose a truss from the <b>geometry</b> menu (Warren, Pratt, Howe, a simple triangle or a cantilever bracket). The supports are a pin and a roller, giving r = 3.</li>
            <li>Set the <b>load</b> magnitude and pick the loaded joint; the downward arrow appears at that joint.</li>
            <li>Press <b>Solve</b>. The full equilibrium system is assembled and solved; members turn <b>red for tension</b> and <b>cyan for compression</b>, with line thickness scaled to force.</li>
            <li>Read the <b>reactions</b> and the per-member <b>force table</b>; zero-force members are greyed.</li>
            <li>Confirm the global checks in the panel: vertical reactions sum to the total load and the moment residual is essentially zero.</li>
            <li>Change the load or geometry and re-solve to see how the force path through the truss changes.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Truss &amp; member forces</span><span class="badge" id="jtStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="jtCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="legend">
                  <span><i style="background:#fca5a5"></i>Tension</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#67e8f9"></i>Compression</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#3a3a48"></i>Zero-force</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#86efac"></i>Reaction</span>
                </div>
                <div class="help"><b>Sign convention:</b> a positive member force is tension (the member pulls its joints inward). Numbers on members are kN; arrows at the supports are the reaction components.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Geometry</label>
                    <select id="jtGeo">
                      <option value="warren">Warren (4 panel)</option>
                      <option value="pratt">Pratt (4 panel)</option>
                      <option value="howe">Howe (4 panel)</option>
                      <option value="tri">Simple triangle</option>
                      <option value="cant">Cantilever bracket</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Load kN</label><input type="range" id="jtP" min="5" max="120" value="40" step="5"><span class="val" id="jtPv">40</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>At joint</label><select id="jtJoint"></select></div>
                  <div class="btns">
                    <button class="btn" id="jtSolve">Solve</button>
                    <button class="btn ghost" id="jtClear">Reset</button>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Members m</div><div class="v" id="jtM">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Joints j</div><div class="v" id="jtJ">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">m + r - 2j</div><div class="v purple" id="jtDet">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Max |force|</div><div class="v amber sm" id="jtMax">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Pin Ax</div><div class="v green sm" id="jtAx">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Pin Ay</div><div class="v green sm" id="jtAy">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Roller By</div><div class="v green sm" id="jtBy">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Moment check</div><div class="v sm" id="jtChk">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="tablewrap">
                    <table class="it"><thead><tr><th>member</th><th>force kN</th><th>state</th></tr></thead><tbody id="jtBody"></tbody></table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="1"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Hibbeler</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis, 10th ed., Ch. 3 (Analysis of Statically Determinate Trusses). Pearson.</li>
            <li><b>Timoshenko &amp; Young</b> &mdash; Theory of Structures, 2nd ed. McGraw-Hill.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis: Analysis of a Truss, sa-nitk.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 2 — METHOD OF SECTIONS ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-2">
          <h2 class="exp-head">2 &middot; Method of sections</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Pass a cut through a Pratt truss and solve a chosen member directly from equilibrium of one free body</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To find the force in a single chosen truss member directly &mdash; without working joint by joint &mdash; by cutting the truss into two free bodies and applying the equilibrium equations to one of them.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>The <b>method of sections</b> exploits the fact that any free body of a structure in equilibrium must itself be in equilibrium. We pass an imaginary <b>cut</b> through the truss, slicing at most three members whose forces are unknown, and consider the equilibrium of everything on one side of the cut. Because a rigid body in a plane has exactly three independent equations, one cut through three members lets us solve all three &mdash; or any one of them in a single equation by choosing a clever moment centre.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Sum Fx = 0,&nbsp; Sum Fy = 0,&nbsp; Sum M(P) = 0 &nbsp;(for the free body on one side of the cut)</div>
            <p>To isolate one diagonal, sum vertical forces &mdash; the horizontal chords contribute nothing &mdash; so the diagonal carries the net shear across the cut. To isolate a chord, take <b>moments about the joint where the diagonal and the other chord meet</b>; their lines of action pass through that point and drop out, leaving one equation in the chord force. The cut force is drawn as tension (arrow pulling away from the free body); a negative result means compression.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Diagonal: Sum Fy = 0 &rArr; (net shear) + N(diag) &middot; sin(theta) = 0<br>Chord: Sum M(joint) = 0 &rArr; N(chord) &middot; (lever arm) = moment of external loads on the free body</div>
            <p>The method is the engineer's shortcut: to grade one member of a large bridge truss you need not march through every joint &mdash; one well-placed section gives the answer immediately. Here the cut is shown as a dashed line, the chosen free body is shaded, and the chosen member force is solved and cross-checked against the full joint solution.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. A Pratt truss with its reactions already computed is shown.</li>
            <li>Set the panel <b>load</b>. The reactions update from global equilibrium.</li>
            <li>Choose a <b>cut</b> position (between panels). The dashed section line appears, the members it crosses are highlighted, and the left free body is shaded.</li>
            <li>Pick the <b>member</b> to solve from the crossed members. The solver writes the equilibrium equation that isolates it.</li>
            <li>Read the <b>worked equation</b> in the log and the resulting force, with tension or compression labelled. Use <b>Show all</b> to list every crossed member at once.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Section cut</span><span class="badge" id="scStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="scCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help"><b>Shaded region</b> is the free body kept for equilibrium. The dashed line is the cut; highlighted members are exposed by it. The amber member is the one being solved.</div>
                <div class="log" id="scLog"></div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Load kN</label><input type="range" id="scP" min="5" max="100" value="30" step="5"><span class="val" id="scPv">30</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Cut at</label>
                    <select id="scCut">
                      <option value="0">Panel 1 | 2</option>
                      <option value="1" selected>Panel 2 | 3</option>
                      <option value="2">Panel 3 | 4</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Member</label><select id="scMem"></select></div>
                  <div class="btns">
                    <button class="btn" id="scSolve">Solve member</button>
                    <button class="btn ghost" id="scAll">Show all</button>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Reaction Ay</div><div class="v green sm" id="scAy">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Reaction By</div><div class="v green sm" id="scBy">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Member force</div><div class="v amber" id="scF">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">State</div><div class="v sm" id="scState">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help"><b>Method:</b> summing vertical forces on the free body isolates a diagonal; moments about the joint where two unwanted members meet isolates a chord.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="2"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Hibbeler</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis, 10th ed., Sec. 3.5 (The Method of Sections). Pearson.</li>
            <li><b>Kassimali</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis, 6th ed., Ch. 4. Cengage.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis: Method of Sections, sa-nitk.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 3 — SFD / BMD ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-3">
          <h2 class="exp-head">3 &middot; Shear-force &amp; bending-moment diagrams</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Build any combination of point loads, distributed loads and applied moments on a simply-supported or cantilever beam</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To compute and plot the shear-force diagram (SFD) and bending-moment diagram (BMD) for a beam carrying point loads, uniformly distributed loads and applied couples, and to read off the maximum shear and maximum bending moment with their locations.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>Cut the beam at a distance x from the left and consider the left free body. The <b>shear force</b> V(x) is the algebraic sum of all transverse forces to the left; the <b>bending moment</b> M(x) is the sum of their moments about the cut. With the sagging-positive convention, V and M obey the fundamental differential relations:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">dV/dx = &minus; w(x) &nbsp;&nbsp;and&nbsp;&nbsp; dM/dx = V(x)</div>
            <p>So under a uniform load w the shear varies linearly and the moment parabolically; under no load the shear is constant and the moment linear. A <b>point load</b> P makes a jump of &minus;P in V; an <b>applied couple</b> M0 makes a jump in M; the moment is locally maximum where V passes through zero (dM/dx = 0). Integrating from the left:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">V(x) = R(left) &minus; (sum of point loads to left) &minus; (integral of w to left)<br>M(x) = integral of V dx &minus; (sum of applied couples to left)</div>
            <p>For a <b>simply supported</b> span the two reactions follow from sum of moments = 0 and sum of vertical forces = 0; for a <b>cantilever</b> the fixed end supplies a vertical reaction and a fixing moment. The solver samples x finely along the span, accumulates V and M exactly using these rules, and draws both diagrams with their extreme values marked.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. Pick the <b>beam type</b> (simply supported or cantilever) and its <b>length</b> L.</li>
            <li>Add loads: a <b>point load</b> at position a, a <b>UDL</b> w over an interval a to b, or an <b>applied moment</b> at a point. Use the add button; each load is listed and can be removed.</li>
            <li>The <b>reactions</b> are recomputed instantly and the SFD (cyan) and BMD (amber) are redrawn beneath the loaded beam.</li>
            <li>Read <b>Vmax</b>, <b>Mmax</b> and the location of the maximum moment &mdash; note it coincides with the point where the shear crosses zero.</li>
            <li>Try a central point load, then spread it as a UDL of the same total, and compare the peak moments.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Beam, SFD &amp; BMD</span><span class="badge" id="sfStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="sfCv" width="680" height="500"></canvas>
                <div class="legend">
                  <span><i style="background:#67e8f9"></i>Shear V(x)</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#fbbf24"></i>Moment M(x)</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#86efac"></i>Reaction</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Beam &amp; loads</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Type</label>
                    <div class="seg" style="flex:1">
                      <div class="opt on" data-sfbeam="ss">Simply sup.</div>
                      <div class="opt" data-sfbeam="cant">Cantilever</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Length m</label><input type="range" id="sfL" min="2" max="12" value="8" step="0.5"><span class="val" id="sfLv">8</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Add</label>
                    <select id="sfKind">
                      <option value="P">Point load (kN)</option>
                      <option value="w">UDL (kN/m)</option>
                      <option value="M">Moment (kN&middot;m)</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Mag</label><input type="number" id="sfMag" value="20" step="1"><label style="min-width:20px">a</label><input type="number" id="sfA" value="4" step="0.5"></div>
                  <div class="row" id="sfP2row"><label>to b</label><input type="number" id="sfB" value="8" step="0.5"><button class="btn" id="sfAdd">Add load</button></div>
                  <div class="row" id="sfP1row" style="justify-content:flex-end"><button class="btn" id="sfAdd2">Add load</button></div>
                  <div class="btns">
                    <button class="btn cyan" id="sfDemo">Example</button>
                    <button class="btn red" id="sfClr">Clear loads</button>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Reaction R(A)</div><div class="v green sm" id="sfRA">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k" id="sfRBk">Reaction R(B)</div><div class="v green sm" id="sfRB">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">V max</div><div class="v sm" id="sfVmax">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">M max</div><div class="v amber sm" id="sfMmax">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help" style="margin-top:8px"><b>Loads</b></div>
                  <div class="tablewrap" style="max-height:150px">
                    <table class="it"><thead><tr><th>type</th><th>mag</th><th>at</th><th></th></tr></thead><tbody id="sfBody"></tbody></table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="3"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Hibbeler</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis, 10th ed., Ch. 4 (Internal Loadings &mdash; Shear and Moment Diagrams). Pearson.</li>
            <li><b>Gere &amp; Goodno</b> &mdash; Mechanics of Materials, 9th ed., Ch. 4. Cengage.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Strength of Materials: Bending Moment in a Beam, mm-coep.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 4 — DEFLECTION ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-4">
          <h2 class="exp-head">4 &middot; Beam deflection by double integration</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">The elastic curve from the Macaulay bracket method, with slope, deflection and the maximum deflection located</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To obtain the deflected shape (elastic curve) of a beam by integrating the bending-moment equation twice using the Macaulay step-function method, applying the support boundary conditions, and to locate and report the maximum deflection.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>For small deflections the curvature of the neutral axis is proportional to the bending moment. The <b>Euler-Bernoulli</b> beam equation relates the transverse deflection y(x) to M(x):</p>
            <div class="eqblock">EI &middot; d&sup2;y/dx&sup2; = M(x)</div>
            <p>Integrating once gives the slope EI&middot;dy/dx and again gives EI&middot;y, each step introducing a constant of integration. The <b>Macaulay method</b> writes the moment with bracket terms (x &minus; a) that are taken as zero when x is less than a, so one single expression covers the whole beam and integrates termwise &mdash; a point load contributes a bracket of power one, a UDL a bracket of power two:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">EI y'' = R&middot;x &minus; P&lt;x&minus;a&gt; &minus; (w/2)&lt;x&minus;c&gt;&sup2;<br>EI y' = R x&sup2;/2 &minus; (P/2)&lt;x&minus;a&gt;&sup2; &minus; (w/6)&lt;x&minus;c&gt;&sup3; + C1<br>EI y = R x&sup3;/6 &minus; (P/6)&lt;x&minus;a&gt;&sup3; &minus; (w/24)&lt;x&minus;c&gt;&#8308; + C1 x + C2</div>
            <p>The constants C1 and C2 follow from the boundary conditions: zero deflection at both supports of a simply supported beam, or zero deflection and zero slope at the fixed end of a cantilever. The <b>maximum deflection</b> occurs where the slope y' is zero; the solver scans for that point. Results scale inversely with the flexural rigidity EI, so doubling EI halves the deflection.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. Choose the <b>support</b> (simply supported or cantilever) and set <b>length</b> L and rigidity <b>EI</b>.</li>
            <li>Choose a standard <b>load case</b> &mdash; central point load, off-centre point load or full UDL (for the cantilever, an end load, a load at a, or full UDL) &mdash; and set its magnitude.</li>
            <li>The <b>elastic curve</b> is drawn (exaggerated), with the slope and deflection at any queried x available below.</li>
            <li>Read the <b>maximum deflection</b> and its location; compare it with the classic closed-form value shown for the standard case.</li>
            <li>Increase <b>EI</b> and watch the curve flatten in inverse proportion; move the query marker to inspect slope and deflection along the beam.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Elastic curve</span><span class="badge" id="dfStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="dfCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help"><b>Deflection is exaggerated</b> for clarity &mdash; the readouts are the true values in millimetres. The dashed line is the undeflected beam; the cyan marker is your query point and the amber marker is the maximum.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Support</label>
                    <div class="seg" style="flex:1">
                      <div class="opt on" data-dfsup="ss">Simply sup.</div>
                      <div class="opt" data-dfsup="cant">Cantilever</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Case</label><select id="dfCase"></select></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Load</label><input type="range" id="dfP" min="2" max="80" value="20" step="2"><span class="val" id="dfPv">20</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Pos a</label><input type="range" id="dfA" min="0.5" max="9.5" value="2" step="0.25"><span class="val" id="dfAv">2</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Length</label><input type="range" id="dfL" min="2" max="10" value="6" step="0.5"><span class="val" id="dfLv">6</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>EI</label><input type="range" id="dfEI" min="2000" max="40000" value="12000" step="1000"><span class="val" id="dfEIv">12000</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Query x</label><input type="range" id="dfQ" min="0" max="6" value="3" step="0.1"><span class="val" id="dfQv">3.0</span></div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">y(max) mm</div><div class="v amber" id="dfYmax">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">at x = m</div><div class="v purple sm" id="dfXmax">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">y(query) mm</div><div class="v green sm" id="dfYq">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">slope(query)</div><div class="v sm" id="dfSq">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help" id="dfClosed" style="margin-top:10px"></div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="4"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Hibbeler</b> &mdash; Structural Analysis, 10th ed., Ch. 8 (Deflections &mdash; Double Integration / Macaulay). Pearson.</li>
            <li><b>Gere &amp; Goodno</b> &mdash; Mechanics of Materials, 9th ed., Ch. 9 (Deflections of Beams). Cengage.</li>
            <li><b>Roark &amp; Young</b> &mdash; Formulas for Stress and Strain, beam deflection tables. McGraw-Hill.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 5 — INFLUENCE LINES ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-5">
          <h2 class="exp-head">5 &middot; Influence lines</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Sweep a unit load across a simply-supported span and trace the influence line for a reaction, shear or moment at a chosen section</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To construct the influence line for a chosen response quantity &mdash; a support reaction, or the shear or bending moment at a fixed section &mdash; by moving a unit load across the span, and to use it to find the load position that maximises that response.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>An <b>influence line</b> plots the value of one structural response (say the moment at a section C) as a function of the position of a single moving unit load. It answers a different question from a bending-moment diagram: the BMD shows M at every section for a fixed load, while the influence line shows one quantity as the load travels. Influence lines are the basis of design for moving loads &mdash; vehicles on bridges, gantry cranes.</p>
            <p>For a simply supported span of length L with a unit load at position a from the left, equilibrium gives the reactions, and these define the lines directly:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Reaction R(A): &nbsp;IL value = (L &minus; a) / L&nbsp;&nbsp;(falls linearly from 1 to 0)<br>Reaction R(B): &nbsp;IL value = a / L</div>
            <p>For shear and moment at a section a distance c from the left support, evaluating V and M as the load passes left and right of C gives two straight segments meeting at C:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Shear at C: &nbsp;IL = &minus;a/L for a &lt; c,&nbsp; IL = (L&minus;a)/L for a &gt; c &nbsp;(jump of 1 at C)<br>Moment at C: &nbsp;IL = a(L&minus;c)/L for a &le; c,&nbsp; IL = c(L&minus;a)/L for a &gt; c &nbsp;(peak c(L&minus;c)/L at a = c)</div>
            <p>By the <b>Muller-Breslau principle</b> the influence line for any reaction or internal action has the shape of the deflected structure produced by releasing that action and giving it a unit displacement &mdash; which is exactly the piecewise-linear shapes above for a determinate beam. The solver sweeps the unit load, evaluates the chosen response at each step, traces the influence line, and reports its peak value and the critical load position.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. Set the span <b>length</b> L and the <b>section</b> position c (for shear/moment influence lines).</li>
            <li>Choose the <b>response</b>: reaction R(A), reaction R(B), shear at C, or moment at C.</li>
            <li>Press <b>Sweep</b> (or drag the load slider). The moving load animates across the span and the influence line is traced point by point beneath.</li>
            <li>Read the <b>ordinate</b> under the current load position &mdash; that is the response value if the unit load sat there.</li>
            <li>Read the <b>peak</b> ordinate and its <b>critical position</b>; placing the heaviest wheel there maximises the response. Note the unit jump of the shear influence line right at the section.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Moving load &amp; influence line</span><span class="badge" id="ilStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="ilCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help"><b>Top</b>: the beam with the unit load at its current position. <b>Bottom</b>: the influence line for the chosen response &mdash; the ordinate under the load is the response value. Positive ordinates lie above the baseline.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Response</label>
                    <select id="ilResp">
                      <option value="RA">Reaction R(A)</option>
                      <option value="RB">Reaction R(B)</option>
                      <option value="V">Shear at C</option>
                      <option value="M" selected>Moment at C</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Length</label><input type="range" id="ilL" min="4" max="14" value="10" step="0.5"><span class="val" id="ilLv">10</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Section c</label><input type="range" id="ilC" min="0.5" max="9.5" value="4" step="0.25"><span class="val" id="ilCv">4</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Load at</label><input type="range" id="ilPos" min="0" max="10" value="3" step="0.1"><span class="val" id="ilPosv">3.0</span></div>
                  <div class="btns">
                    <button class="btn" id="ilSweep">Sweep</button>
                    <button class="btn ghost" id="ilStop">Stop</button>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Ordinate now</div><div class="v green" id="ilNow">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Peak ordinate</div><div class="v amber" id="ilPeak">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Critical pos m</div><div class="v purple sm" id="ilCrit">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Units</div><div class="v sm" id="ilUnit">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help"><b>To maximise the response</b> from a single concentrated load, place it at the critical position; for a UDL the response is the load intensity times the net area under the influence line.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="5"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
