      { q: 'Why must each joint be analysed in an order where it has at most two unknown member forces?',
        o: ['To save time', 'Because a joint provides only two scalar equilibrium equations', 'To avoid compression', 'Because of symmetry'], a: 1,
        e: 'A concurrent (joint) force system gives exactly two equations Fx=0 and Fy=0, solving at most two unknowns.' }
    ],
    '2': [
      { q: 'The method of sections is most efficient when you need:',
        o: ['Every member force', 'The force in one or a few specific members', 'Only the reactions', 'The deflection'], a: 1,
        e: 'One well-placed cut isolates a target member directly, without marching through every joint.' },
      { q: 'A single straight section should ideally cut no more than how many members with unknown forces?',
        o: ['Two', 'Three', 'Four', 'Five'], a: 1,
        e: 'A planar free body has three equilibrium equations, so a section cutting three unknowns is solvable.' },
      { q: 'To solve a chord member directly, you usually take moments about:',
        o: ['The mid-span', 'The joint where the diagonal and the other chord meet', 'The nearest support only', 'The loaded joint'], a: 1,
        e: 'Choosing that joint as the moment centre eliminates the two unwanted members, leaving one equation.' },
      { q: 'The method of sections relies on the principle that:',
        o: ['Only the whole structure is in equilibrium', 'Any isolated portion of a body in equilibrium is itself in equilibrium', 'Members carry shear', 'Reactions are always equal'], a: 1,
        e: 'Cutting and keeping one free body works because each part of an equilibrium system is in equilibrium.' }
    ],
    '3': [
      { q: 'The relationship between shear V and distributed load intensity w along a beam is:',
        o: ['dV/dx = M', 'dV/dx = -w', 'dV/dx = w x', 'V = M / x'], a: 1,
        e: 'Differentiating equilibrium of a slice gives dV/dx = -w.' },
      { q: 'The bending moment is a local maximum (or minimum) at the section where:',
        o: ['The load is largest', 'The shear force passes through zero', 'The beam is deepest', 'The reaction acts'], a: 1,
        e: 'Since dM/dx = V, the moment is stationary where V = 0.' },
      { q: 'A concentrated point load on a beam causes the shear-force diagram to:',
        o: ['Curve parabolically', 'Have a sudden jump (step)', 'Stay constant through it', 'Become zero'], a: 1,
        e: 'A point load produces a vertical step equal to the load in the shear diagram.' },
      { q: 'Under a uniformly distributed load, the bending-moment diagram is:',
        o: ['Constant', 'Linear', 'Parabolic', 'A step function'], a: 2,
        e: 'With V linear under a UDL, M (its integral) is parabolic.' }
    ],
    '4': [
      { q: 'The Euler-Bernoulli equation relating deflection to bending moment is:',
        o: ['EI y = M', 'EI dy/dx = M', 'EI d2y/dx2 = M', 'EI d3y/dx3 = M'], a: 2,
        e: 'Curvature equals M/(EI), so EI times the second derivative of y equals the bending moment.' },
      { q: 'The Macaulay (bracket) method handles point and distributed loads by:',
        o: ['Ignoring discontinuities', 'Using step terms that vanish before their start point', 'Always splitting the beam into separate equations', 'Using numerical integration only'], a: 1,
        e: 'A bracket term (x-a)^n is taken as zero for x below a, giving one continuous expression to integrate.' },
      { q: 'For a simply supported beam, the constants of integration are fixed by the conditions:',
        o: ['Zero slope at both ends', 'Zero deflection at both supports', 'Zero moment at mid-span', 'Maximum slope at supports'], a: 1,
        e: 'Both supports prevent deflection, giving y = 0 at each support to solve C1 and C2.' },
      { q: 'For a central point load P on a simply supported span L, the maximum deflection is:',
        o: ['P L^3 / (3 EI)', 'P L^3 / (48 EI)', '5 P L^4 / (384 EI)', 'P L / (EI)'], a: 1,
        e: 'The classic result for a mid-span point load is P L^3 / (48 EI) at the centre.' }
    ],
    '5': [
      { q: 'An influence line shows how a single response quantity varies as a function of:',
        o: ['The section position for a fixed load', 'The position of a moving unit load', 'Time', 'The beam depth'], a: 1,
        e: 'It plots one response (e.g. moment at C) versus the position of a moving unit load.' },
      { q: 'For a simply supported span L, the influence line for reaction R(A) is:',
        o: ['Constant at 1', 'A straight line from 1 at A to 0 at B', 'Parabolic', 'Zero everywhere'], a: 1,
        e: 'R(A) = (L - a)/L falls linearly from 1 (load over A) to 0 (load over B).' },
      { q: 'The influence line for shear at a section C has a characteristic:',
        o: ['Smooth peak', 'Unit jump (step) right at C', 'Flat top', 'Parabolic shape'], a: 1,
        e: 'As the load crosses C the shear changes abruptly, producing a jump of one in the influence line.' },
      { q: 'The Muller-Breslau principle states that an influence line has the shape of:',
        o: ['The bending-moment diagram', 'The deflected shape when the corresponding restraint is released and given a unit displacement', 'The shear diagram', 'A parabola always'], a: 1,
        e: 'Releasing the action and imposing a unit displacement traces the influence line shape directly.' }
    ],
    '6': [
      { q: 'The Euler critical load for a column is proportional to:',
        o: ['1 / (KL)', '1 / (KL)^2', '(KL)^2', 'KL'], a: 1,
        e: 'P_cr = pi^2 E I / (KL)^2, so it falls with the square of the effective length.' },
      { q: 'The effective length factor K for a fixed-free (flagpole) column is:',
        o: ['0.5', '0.7', '1.0', '2.0'], a: 3,
        e: 'A column fixed at the base and free at the top has K = 2, the most flexible case.' },
      { q: 'The slenderness ratio of a column is defined as:',
        o: ['A / I', 'K L / r', 'E / sigma', 'P / A'], a: 1,
        e: 'Slenderness lambda = K L / r, with r the radius of gyration of the cross-section.' },
      { q: 'Euler buckling theory ceases to apply, and yielding governs instead, when the column is:',
        o: ['Very slender (large lambda)', 'Short / stocky (small lambda)', 'Made of steel', 'Loaded eccentrically'], a: 1,
        e: 'For stocky columns the Euler stress exceeds the yield stress, so material yielding/crushing governs first.' }
    ]
  };

  function buildQuiz(host) {
    var qid = host.getAttribute('data-quiz');
    var qs = QUIZZES[qid]; if (!qs) return;
    var selections = new Array(qs.length).fill(-1);
    var checked = false;
    for (var i = 0; i < qs.length; i++) {
      (function (item, idx) {
        var card = document.createElement('div');
        card.className = 'q';
        var qt = document.createElement('div');
        qt.className = 'qt';
        qt.innerHTML = '<b>Q' + (idx + 1) + '.</b> ' + item.q;
        card.appendChild(qt);
        var opts = [];
        for (var j = 0; j < item.o.length; j++) {
          (function (optIdx) {
            var op = document.createElement('div');
            op.className = 'opt-a';
            op.textContent = item.o[optIdx];
            op.addEventListener('click', function () {
              if (checked) return;
              selections[idx] = optIdx;
              for (var m = 0; m < opts.length; m++) opts[m].classList.remove('sel');
              op.classList.add('sel');
            });
            opts.push(op);
            card.appendChild(op);
          })(j);
        }
        var expl = document.createElement('div');
        expl.className = 'expl';
        expl.innerHTML = '<b>Answer:</b> ' + item.o[item.a] + '. ' + item.e;
        card.appendChild(expl);
        host.appendChild(card);
        host._cards = host._cards || []; host._cards.push({ card: card, opts: opts, item: item, idx: idx });
      })(qs[i], i);
    }
    var foot = document.createElement('div');
    foot.className = 'quizfoot';
    var btn = document.createElement('button');
    btn.className = 'btn green'; btn.textContent = 'Check answers';
    var score = document.createElement('div'); score.className = 'score';
    foot.appendChild(btn); foot.appendChild(score);
    host.appendChild(foot);

    btn.addEventListener('click', function () {
      if (!checked) {
        checked = true; var correct = 0;
        for (var c = 0; c < host._cards.length; c++) {
          var rec = host._cards[c];
          var sel = selections[rec.idx];
          for (var m = 0; m < rec.opts.length; m++) {
            rec.opts[m].classList.remove('sel');
            if (m === rec.item.a) rec.opts[m].classList.add('correct');
            else if (m === sel) rec.opts[m].classList.add('wrong');
          }
          if (sel === rec.item.a) correct++; else rec.card.classList.add('bad');
          rec.card.querySelector('.expl').classList.add('show');
        }
        score.innerHTML = 'Score: <b>' + correct + ' / ' + host._cards.length + '</b>';
        btn.textContent = 'Reset';
      } else {
        checked = false; selections = new Array(qs.length).fill(-1);
        for (var c2 = 0; c2 < host._cards.length; c2++) {
          var rec2 = host._cards[c2];
          rec2.card.classList.remove('bad');
          rec2.card.querySelector('.expl').classList.remove('show');
          for (var m2 = 0; m2 < rec2.opts.length; m2++) rec2.opts[m2].className = 'opt-a';
        }
        score.innerHTML = ''; btn.textContent = 'Check answers';
      }
    });
  }
  var quizHosts = document.querySelectorAll('.stx .quiz');
  for (var qh = 0; qh < quizHosts.length; qh++) buildQuiz(quizHosts[qh]);

  // initial draw of experiment 1
  if (REDRAW['1']) { try { REDRAW['1'](); } catch (e) {} }
  window.addEventListener('resize', function () {
    var onExp = document.querySelector('.stx .exp.on');
    if (onExp) { var n = onExp.id.split('-')[1]; if (REDRAW[n]) { try { REDRAW[n](); } catch (e) {} } }
  });
})();
</script>
